03746nam a22005055i 9780773575783DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20092009xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735757837 a10.1515/97807735757832doi  a(DE-B1597)657949  a(OCoLC)741350254  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aND1340 ǂb M49713 2009eb 7aART0150002bisacsh04a758/.11 aMilani, Raffaele, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aArt of the Landscape /cRaffaele Milani. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (216 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tPathways -- tAesthetics of the Environment -- tWhat Is the Landscape? -- tThe Sentimental Journey -- tCategories -- tThe Art of the Landscape -- tContemplation of the Landscape -- tMorphologies -- tMorphology of Natural Beauties -- tThe Mirror of the Senses and of Reason -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAesthetics deals with art, a human construction, but what one experiences when placed before nature is also an aesthetic feeling - the countryside is a place of reflection like no other. In The Art of the Landscape, Raffaele Milani interprets natural landscapes as an aesthetic category. Drawing from philosophical traditions, literature, and art, he calls the reader's attention to a special consciousness, originally established during the pre-Romantic age, that has become a distinctive feature of contemporary spirituality. Focusing on the definition of landscapes in relation to the concepts of nature, environment, territory, and man-made settings such as gardens and cities, Milani examines the origins of the predilection for natural scenery in the works of landscape painters and in travel literature. He addresses the distinctness of the aesthetic experience of landscapes, analyses the role of aesthetic categories, and explores landscape art as a medium of contemplation. What emerges is an original morphology of natural beauty derived from the scrutiny of landscape elements most frequently associated with aesthetic emotion - the colour of water and the sky, earth and stones, fire and volcanic eruptions, ruins and the mountains - an analysis especially relevant given the increasing fragility of our natural environment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aART / History / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077357578340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773575783423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773575783/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles